      <hedline>
        <hl1>About Bad Fits</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Letter from Dr Peter G Hill, chiropractor, complains that medical doctors too often try to redirect patients away from chiropractors (April 25 article on dysfunctional doctor-patient relationships)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>''Even Doctor-Patient Relationships Can Be Dysfunctional'' highlights the problem of using a medical gatekeeper for alternative care like chiropractic.</p>
        <p>The medical doctor in this column, as too often occurs, tries to redirect the patient away from the chiropractor.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>''Even Doctor-Patient Relationships Can Be Dysfunctional'' highlights the problem of using a medical gatekeeper for alternative care like chiropractic.</p>
        <p>The medical doctor in this column, as too often occurs, tries to redirect the patient away from the chiropractor.</p>
        <p>When this particular patient demands what she rightly deserves, an unfettered referral, she is labeled difficult.</p>
        <p>It is the doctors who truly deserve the label.</p>
        <p>Medical doctors should not be in charge of referrals to alternative providers for which they have no knowledge or training. And patients should be allowed to choose alternative providers so that they can get the care they need, when they need it.</p>
        <p>DR . PETER  G. HILL  Boston</p>
        <p>The writer is a chiropractor.</p>
      </block>
